The [JIRA data anonymiser|http://confluence.atlassian.com/display/JIRA/Anonymising+data] doesn't replace non-English characters. Replacing the two occurrences of the following line in the {{anon.stx}} template:

{code}
<stx:value-of select="translate(., '0123456789abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyzABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZ', 'xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx')"/>
{code}

...with this...

{code}
<stx:value-of select="string-pad('x', string-length(.))"/>
{code}

...will replace all characters, English or not.

Emphasise on a need of granting the Browse project permission in order to the depending permissions take effect.

http://confluence.atlassian.com/display/JIRA/Managing+Project+Permissions 

{quote}
One thing I may suggest is that you update your documentation on http://confluence.atlassian.com/display/JIRA/Managing+Project+Permissions to show how important the 'Browse Project' permission really is in the Project Permission table. While I knew that it effected the visibility of issues and projects, the 'Work On Issues' permission does not indicate that this is dependent on being able to view the issue. 
{quote}

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-23022].
  {panel}

_Case scenario:_
Granting project permissions that depends on Browse Project should be allowed only, if the browse permission is granted.

Currently, JIRA will happily grant permissions such as 'Work On Issues' to any users despite that they may not have rights to view a given project. 

Most modern applications don't allow assign permissions that violate constrains imposed by a 'super' permission. Lack of the permission validation in JIRA sets silently unaware JIRA admin for a nightmare of troubleshooting permission...


Feedback from a customer:
{quote}
... While I knew that it effected the visibility of issues and projects, the 'Work On Issues' permission does not indicate that this is dependent on being able to view the issue. 

We tried a scenario where we would send the user a link to the log work for a particular issue and it stated the did not have permission to view the issue, which while technically correct, is not indicated with the 'Work On Issue' permission.
{quote}

According to the [Integrating Crowd with Atlassian JIRA|http://confluence.atlassian.com/display/CROWD/Integrating+Crowd+with+Atlassian+JIRA] documentation, Step 2.2.3, if you're going to enable SSO and are running JIRA 4.2 you should uncomment the following line from {{$JIRA_INSTALL/atlassian-jira/WEB-INF/classes/seraph-config.xml}}:

{code:xml}
<authenticator class="com.atlassian.crowd.integration.seraph.v22.JIRAAuthenticator"/>
{code}

However, after having done this you're actually unable to log into JIRA at _all_, either with the built-in JIRA user database or Crowd's. Commenting that line out and restarting JIRA results in being able to log in correctly via Crowd's user database (but obviously you then don't get SSO).

I've verified this with a clean install of both JIRA 4.2 and Crowd 2.0.7.

