h3. Problem Definition
Currently , there's no way to filter issue using email domain . It can often be helpful to search for all issues reported by a reporting user's email domain, perhaps not so much w/AOL or gmail, but certainly with corporate domains. Please enable either the contains operator for reporter or add a function to get email domain from reporter or similar solution. 

h3. Suggested Solution
Provide a JQL query , for example :-
{noformat}
reporter in emaildomainOf("customer1.com") ...
{noformat}

When the REST API reports the type of a field that the user can supply for a transition, it returns the actual class name that is used internally by JIRA. Example:

{noformat}GET rest/api/2.0/issue/HSP-1/transitions{noformat}

Returns:

{noformat}
{
   "Close Issue":[
      {
         "name":"resolution",
         "required":true,
         "type":"com.atlassian.jira.issue.resolution.Resolution"
      },
      {
         "name":"fixVersions",
         "required":false,
         "type":"com.atlassian.jira.project.version.Version"
      },
      {
         "name":"assignee",
         "required":false,
         "type":"com.opensymphony.user.User"
      }
   ],
   "Resolve Issue":[
      {
         "name":"resolution",
         "required":true,
         "type":"com.atlassian.jira.issue.resolution.Resolution"
      },
      {
         "name":"fixVersions",
         "required":false,
         "type":"com.atlassian.jira.project.version.Version"
      },
      {
         "name":"assignee",
         "required":false,
         "type":"com.opensymphony.user.User"
      }
   ],
   "Start Progress":[

   ]
}
{noformat}

Shouldn't we shield clients from such implementation-specific details?

Also, this doesn't work very well for custom fields since we don't necessarily know the class that is used internally by third-party custom fields.

We should come up with a way of representing the type information that makes sense for both built-in and custom fields (perhaps in the scope of JRADEV-2783).

